Comment:
*Facepalm*
What is it with people and hating Anthropomorphic animals?
Hey geniuses, not all furries draw or enjoy porn.
Furries are not all about porn, and if you think that, I highly recommend checking out a webcomic called "Zoophobia".
I actually think this is a pretty funny concept. Besides, we have cartoons like Mikey Mouse, Looney Tunes and MANY others, where animals are Anthropomorphic. They don't have anything to do with Furry porn.Â 
Seriously, having Animals as main characters has been around forever and I really like that idea.
Besides, EVERYTHING has porn. Everything. So shut the hell up.

Anyways, for some reason, I just can't get enough of this trailer, I find myself coming back to it time and time again.
The animation is very smooth and the expressions are pretty nice and the concept of the trailer is hilarious, especially with the narrator expressing little to no emotion, and I like the fact that natural enemies don't get along.
I also like how they walk differently, similar to how animals walk differently. 
I can't wait to see this movie.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment:
Through out reading a lot of comments here, I am seeing some place a connection with the ongoing webcomic, Zoophobia. Yes there are reason to connect the two, one the names being similar and two, the silly pun. BUT seriously guys, this film as far as we can all tell, will strictly be about anthro's (no humans) nor will it likely revolve around a school and students (the fox appears to be the main character and he looks like he works at a office). Though Zoophobia is a cool comic and I check up on it weekly myself, I doubt a percentage of people working on this film has ever came across this comic and just figured up a title for the film sort like the author to the comic did. One placed phobia cause the main character is scared of said animals. The other Topia because its a city full of anthros.Â 
I'm super hyped about this film nonetheless and hope it has a great story plot. I've been waiting to see Disney do a anthro film again (with no humans at ALL) for quite awhile.

Comment: See, I have a better idea. A movie that opens up to a superhero saving the day. After a mighty battle with his enemy and a daring rescue of a little girl from radioactive doom, our yet unnamed hero returns to his home, exhausted and a mess...ew...radioactive sweaty super-underwear...atleast it's the outer pair for over his pants. ANYWAY. He casually tosses his dirty clothes in the hamper despite his wife yelling from downstairs to remember his costume goes in the special bin not the regular hamper, and he tiredly staggers off to take a shower. Welllll....when he steps out and goes to find some clean clothes for the evening, the hamper is missing. His wife screams from down stairs and as he rushes awkwardly down the stairs in his towel, he discovers a now LIVING clothes hamper monster trying to eat his wife's oven mit while she tries to wrestle the mit back. The creature panics and escapes, and soon reports of a wandering laundry monster stealing and eatting people's socks pop up all over the neighborhood. People from all walks and groups try to stop the beast, but it keep escaping. A lazy little boy discovers the hamper monster in his backyard, and finds out if he feeds the monster his dirty clothes...he doesn't have to wash them. Ever. So he decides to try and hide it and keep it as a pet, to make cleaning his room easier. Adventure, childhood pet keeping love, drama, and a few tense scenes ensue and in a dramatic battle between the hero hubby in deep doo doo and the hamper monster who mistakenly thinks he has to defend or protect the boy from the hero...the hamper breaks. All smelly missing laundry appears in a massive pile from seemingly out of no where in the middle of the road where the hamper now lay ordinary, plastic, and broken in half. The boy begins to weep. Falling to his knees and bawling, something stirs in the mountain of lost dirty clothes...a pile of baby hamper beasts no bigger than decks of cards leap up and scatter off away. People shriek but the boy is over joyed. These tiny hamper monsters move into homes all acrossed the globe, hiding behind clothes dryers and feasting on the left socks of the world.

Comment:
This trailer gets so many things wrong, it just make me cringe.Â  Let's list them, shall we?
- Right off the bat:Â  Humans *are* animals.Â  You can try and separate them all you want, but humans belong to same Kingdom Animalia as every other mammal, fish, amphibian, reptile, bird, and invertebrate.Â  Would have been better to say, "This is not a human." instead of "This is an animal."
- Anthropomorphised means "human-like" in every meaning of the word... not just "it basically walks on two legs".Â  If that were the case, then every animal that already walks on two legs is "anthropomorphic" when they plainly aren't.
- Foxes have hearing far superior to rabbits.
- Crotch-cover when mentioning clothes.Â  Nothing to see in the first place.Â  That old schtick is getting tired.Â  Not to mention, most furred animals have no need for clothes.
- Technology use:Â  Not limited to humans.Â  Many animals use tools, via trial and error, a very basic version of "the scientific method".Â 
- Ignoring the pun:Â  Something we haven't seen before... with everything you've mentioned is in this movie?Â  Ignoring, what, the dozens if not hundreds of animated features from around the world, Disney included, that feature nothing but anthropomorphic animals wearing clothes and doing human-like activities in natural conflict between their relative species?Â  I don't think so.
- Be-fur.Â  Puns.Â  No.Â  Puns are bad.Â  Especially puns that end in "fur".

I get the impression this trailer was made by a Furry... featuring all the retardation that comes with being one.  It even sounds like it was narrated by a Furry.

I think it will be a fantastic film that children and adults alike will enjoy.

As much as I like how this looks like its going to turn out, my only problem with it is its similarity to a comic/book called Zoophobia that has and still is being written for years by artist and animator Vivienne Medrano, who has put her heart and soul into that book.

I feel sorry for her. Since Disney is an empire in animation and motion picture industry, she can't do anything about it. I would feel terribly awful too if someone bigger and more well-known than me came along, took my idea, bent it a little and said "Hey! Look at this completely original movie I just made up myself!", while I sat in the corner with a comic I've been working on for 8 years, carefully and wholeheartedly devoting myself to, and I could do nothing to change it.

No disrespect to Disney, Zootopia, Zoophobia or Vivienne, of course.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: I can only hope the best for this.Â  The trailer does not give us any real scoop on the plot, if any.Â  I personally enjoyed two franchises loads of people really loved, or really hated that utilized this kind of world:Â  AATC and FiM.Â  A series in a world where high pitched, flat nosed dwarfs exist alongside other people, and another set in a world populated by cute but creepy little horses with marks on their hides.Â  The backlash against the Chipmunks was every bit as powerful as the fandom.Â  The scrutiny that Ponies continue to receive is staggering, yet that doesn't stop fictions and visual arts from being churned out on DA amongst others.Â  Will this movie be a turning point, or will it become a silly fad like the chipmunks and ponies did in two years or less? I can say one thing: It won't make me appreciate Anthro art any less, any more than EQG and AATC 2007 and 2009 made me love chipmunks and ponies any less.Â  If the story pleases me, then I will praise David Seville, Beatrice Miller and Celestia for a great film.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: This looks great, but Disney, nothing we've ever seen "be-fur?" Bad pun aside, we have all seen this before. Disney, YOU have used anthropomorphic creatures in almost all of your movies. This concept itself, of a world made of entirely anthropomorphic animals, is also /not/ an original idea, which you seem to be attempting to pass it off as. There's this thing called the "furry community" (an actually great crowd full of good people that has an unfortunate and unjustified reputation). I'm not complaining, stories/worlds like this are great! And the furry community could definitely use some positive exposure. I just feel like it's kind of a kick in the leg to the countless people who have made stories and graphic novels like this when you say it's "like nothing seen before." Other than that little line, this seems amazing, and I'm pretty excited for it! I'd just be nice if you stopped advertising it in a way that makes it seem like you're trying to sell it as an original concept. Not sure if that was your intent or not, but that's the feeling I got from watching the trailer.

I give Disney major kudos for making a movie using the term "anthropomorphic" correctly, as well as shooting for an original anthropomorphic film period.

So I won't rain on their parade and mention PlayStation's Sly Cooper, Hanna Barbera's SWAT Kats, Nintendo's Star Fox, Dreamwork's Kung Fu Panda or Nickolodeon's Tuff Puppy.

And before anyone says anything, no Barnyard and Nut Job don't count because there are still humans. And certain 50's cartoons with talking animals that act as the mascot for certain mystery solving groups don't count either.

Usually when Disney uses anthropomorphic animals, it is to make a twist upon a tale or trope used before. The only twist here it seems is that humans are animals. Reading the plot from the description, the only way I can see it being interesting is if the small herbivore versus big carnivore animals were symbolism to racism or some sort of discrimination but if it's only the rabbit that is being bullied then the idea of this doesn't seem that original to me.
